Genital organs.
Atrium (at) short. Proximal penis (p) long, slender; becoming slightly broader with short pouch before tapering distally. Penial sheath (ps) thick, extending about fourth-fifths of total penis length; penial sheath retractor muscle (psr) very thin, originating at atrium and body wall (
Fig. 7A
). Vas deferens (vd) long, slender; slightly broadened before tapering distally; passes through about one-tenth of penial sheath length before entering into penis distally (
Fig. 7B
). Penial retractor muscle (pr) thin and very long, inserting distally on penis at the penis and vas deferens junction.

Vagina (v) very short and stout. Gametolytic duct (gd) long, extending as far as albumin gland; gametolytic sac ovate (gs). Free oviduct (fo) long, proximally large with equivalent diameter with vagina, and tapering to smaller tube distally. Oviduct (ov) enlarged and folded; prostate gland inconspicuous and bound to oviduct. Talon (ta) small, short and club shaped. Hermaphroditic duct (hd) bearing seminal vesicle (sv) about as long as the length from talon to branching point of seminal vesicle (
Fig. 7A
).
